Let  
\[
\alpha=\frac{(k-1)\pi}{2n},\qquad \beta=\frac{k\pi}{2n},\qquad h=\beta-\alpha=\frac{\pi}{2n}.
\]
Then \(\alpha+\beta=\frac{(2k-1)\pi}{2n}\), so each summand is
\[
\frac{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}{\cos^2\alpha\,\cos^2\beta}.
\]
Use
\[
\tan\beta+\tan\alpha=\frac{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta},\qquad 
\tan\beta-\tan\alpha=\frac{\sin(\beta-\alpha)}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}=\frac{\sin h}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}.
\]
Hence
\[
\frac{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}{\cos^2\alpha\cos^2\beta}
=\frac{\sin(\alpha+\beta)}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}\cdot \frac{1}{\cos\alpha\cos\beta}
=(\tan\alpha+\tan\beta)\cdot \frac{\tan\beta-\tan\alpha}{\sin h}
=\frac{\tan^2\beta-\tan^2\alpha}{\sin h}.
\]
Therefore the sum telescopes:
\[
a_n=\sum_{k=1}^{n-1}\frac{\tan^2\left(\frac{k\pi}{2n}\right)-\tan^2\left(\frac{(k-1)\pi}{2n}\right)}{\sin h}
=\frac{\tan^2\left(\frac{(n-1)\pi}{2n}\right)-\tan^2(0)}{\sin h}
=\frac{\tan^2\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-h\right)}{\sin h}
=\frac{\cot^2 h}{\sin h}
=\frac{\cos^2 h}{\sin^3 h}.
\]
Now \(h=\frac{\pi}{2n}\to 0\), so \(\cos^2 h\to 1\) and \(\sin h\sim h\). Thus
\[
\frac{a_n}{n^3}
=\frac{\cos^2 h}{n^3\sin^3 h}
\sim \frac{1}{n^3 h^3}
=\frac{1}{n^3\left(\frac{\pi}{2n}\right)^3}
=\frac{8}{\pi^3}.
\]

